==Foreign relations and military==
{{Main|Foreign relations of Afghanistan|Military of Afghanistan}}
The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] is responsible for managing the [[foreign relations of Afghanistan]]. The nation has maintained good [[Afghanistan – United States relations|relations with the United States]] and other members of [[NATO]] since at least the 1920s. Afghanistan joined the [[United Nations]] on November 19, 1946, and has been a member since. In 2002, the [[United Nations Assistance Mission in Afghanistan]] was established to help rebuild the country. Today, more than 22 NATO nations deploy over 100,000 troops in Afghanistan as a part of the [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF). Apart from close military links, Afghanistan also enjoys strong economic relations with NATO members and other allies. The United States is the largest donor to Afghanistan, followed by Japan, United Kingdom, Germany, India and others.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.usaid.gov/policy/budget/cbj2007/ane/af.html |title=USAID: Afghanistan |publisher=Usaid.gov |date=2006-06-07 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[File:US Embassy in Kabul on July 4th 2010.jpg|thumb|The [[U.S. Embassy, Kabul|U.S. Embassy in Kabul]]. [[Afghanistan – United States relations|Afghanistan-United States relations]] go back to at least the early 1920s.]]

[[Afghanistan–Pakistan relations|Relations between Afghanistan and neighboring Pakistan]] often fluctuate and tensions between the two countries have existed since 1947.&lt;ref&gt;Hasnat, Syed Farooq, &quot;Pakistan &amp; Afghanistan: Domestic Pressures and Regional Threats&quot; in Journal of International Affairs, Vol. 63, Fall/Winter 2009, page 141-155, Columbia University [http://jia.sipa.columbia.edu/pakistan%E2%80%99s-strategic-interests-afghanistan-and-fluctuating-us-strategy link] ''&quot;Since 1947, serious differences and tensions have existed between the two respective governments at various phases of Pakistan-Afghanistan relations.&quot;''&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.usip.org/resources/resolving-pakistan-afghanistan-stalemate Resolving the Pakistan-Afghanistan Stalemate], United States Institute of Peace, ''Afghanistan and Pakistan have had largely antagonistic relations under all governments''&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.onwar.com/aced/data/alpha/afghanpakist1961.htm Pashtunistan Crisis 1960–1963], Armed Conflict Events Data (ACED)&lt;/ref&gt; During the Taliban 1996 to 2001 rule, Pakistan was supporting the Taliban leaders&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0109/20/se.17.html |title=Hotline: America's New War, Pakistan's Influence |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date=2001-09-20 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; against the Iranian-backed [[Northern Alliance]].&lt;ref name=&quot;cfr&quot;&gt;{{cite web|author=Greg Bruno and Lionel Beehner |url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/13578/iran_and_the_future_of_afghanistan.html |title=Iran and the Future of Afghanistan - Council on Foreign Relations |publisher=Cfr.org |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; Though Pakistan maintains strong security and economic links with Afghanistan, dispute between the two countries remain due to Pakistani concerns over growing influence of rival India in Afghanistan and the continuing border dispute over the poorly marked [[Durand Line]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cic.nyu.edu/afghanistan/docs/stalemate.pdf |title=Resolving the Pakistan-Afghanistan Stalemate |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; Relations between the two strained further after the [[Afghanistan-Pakistan Skirmishes|2007 border skirmishes]] when Afghan officials alleged that Pakistani intelligence agencies were involved in some terrorist attacks on Afghanistan.&lt;ref name=&quot;dawn.com&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/13+pakistan+stoking+violence+in+afghanistan+adviser-za-01 |title=World &amp;#124; Pakistan stoking violence in Afghanistan: adviser |publisher=Dawn.Com |date=2009-10-15 |accessdate=2009-12-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; Pakistan is a participant in the reconstruction of Afghanistan, pledging $250 million in various projects across the country.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author= |url=http://thepeopleofpakistan.wordpress.com/2010/07/12/pakistan-afghanistan-the-conjoined-twins/ |title=Pakistan-Afghanistan: The Conjoined Twins |publisher=Thepeopleofpakistan.wordpress.com |date=2010-07-12 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Afghanistan has close historical, linguistic and cultural ties with neighboring Iran as both countries were part of [[Greater Persia]] before 1747.&lt;ref&gt;Bruno, G., &quot;Iran and the future of Afghanistan&quot;, Council on Foreign Relations, March 30, 2009 [http://www.cfr.org/publication/13578/iran_and_the_future_of_afghanistan.html] ''&quot;Iran has close linguistic and cultural ties to Afghanistan, particularly with Tajiks, Persian-speaking Afghans in Herat Province, and the Hazara, a Shiite minority residing in central and northern Afghanistan...&quot;''&lt;/ref&gt; [[Afghanistan–Iran relations|Afghanistan-Iran relations]] formally initiated after 1935 between [[Mohammed Zahir Shah|Zahir Shah]] and [[Rezā Shāh|Reza Shah]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}, which soured after the rise of radical [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] Taliban regime in 1997 but rebounded after the establishment of [[Presidency of Hamid Karzai|Karzai government]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.parstimes.com/news/archive/2005/rfe/afghanistan_iran_relations.html |title=Afghanistan/Iran: Relations Between Tehran, Kabul Growing Stronger |publisher=Parstimes.com |date=2005-01-26 |accessdate=2009-12-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; Iran has also actively participated in the Afghan reconstruction efforts&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/27/world/asia/27afghan.ready.html Iran Is Seeking More Influence in Afghanistan]&lt;/ref&gt; but is accused at the same time by [[Politics of the United States|American]] and [[Politics of United Kingdom|British politicians]] of secretly funding the Taliban against NATO-Afghan officials.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/06/12/world/main2919294.shtml |title=U.S.: Iran Transferring Weapons To Taliban |publisher=Cbsnews.com |date=2007-06-12 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; Afghanistan also enjoys good relations with neighboring Central Asian nations, especially [[Uzbekistan]], [[Tajikistan]] and [[Turkmenistan]].

[[Afghanistan–India relations|Relations between Afghanistan and India]] also go a long away back. India is often regarded as one of Afghanistan's most influential allies.&lt;ref name=&quot;autogenerated2&quot;/&gt; India is the largest regional donor to Afghanistan and has extensively participated in several Afghan reconstruction efforts, including power, agricultural and educational projects.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://reliefweb.int/rw/RWFiles2009.nsf/FilesByRWDocUnidFilename/VVOS-7Y4RBQ-full_report.pdf/$File/full_report.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5neRkSkWj|archivedate=2010-02-19 |title=Engaging regional players in Afghanistan |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/2009/11/23/india-afghanistan-manmohan-singh-opinions-contributors-mumbai.html |title=We Need India's Help In Afghanistan |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2009-11-23 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; Since 2002, India has extended more than $1.2 billion in military and other aid to Afghanistan.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mynews.in/News/India,_a_traditional_partner_of_Afghanistan_N30965.html# |title=India, a traditional partner of Afghanistan |publisher=Mynews.in |date=2009-11-24 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; There are military ties between the two nations, some Afghan security forces are getting counter-insurgency training in India.{{Dubious|date=September 2010}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/afghanistan_why_india_s_cooperation_problem_pakistan |title=Afghanistan: Why India's Cooperation is a Problem for Pakistan |publisher=Stratfor.com |date=2008-04-11 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; India is also considering the deployment of some troops in Afghanistan.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Sujan Dutta |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1091204/jsp/frontpage/story_11820686.jsp |title=US feelers on Afghan army – Admiral sounds India on training |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[military of Afghanistan]] is under the [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Defense]], which includes the [[Afghan National Army]] and the [[Afghan National Army Air Force]]. It currently has about 134,000 members and is expected to reach 260,000 in the coming years. They are trained and equipped by NATO countries, mainly by the [[United States armed forces]]. The ANA is divided into 7 major [[Corps]], with the [[201st Corps (Afghanistan)|201st Selab (&quot;Flood&quot;)]] in Kabul being the main one. The ANA also has a special [[ANA Commando Brigade|commando brigade]] which was started in 2007. The [[National Military Academy of Afghanistan]] serves as the main education institute for the militarymen of the country. A new $200 million [[Afghan Defense University]] (ADU) is under construction near the capital.

==Economy==
{{Main|Economy of Afghanistan}}
Afghanistan is an impoverished and [[least developed country]], one of the world's poorest. In 2010, the nation's [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] [[exchange rate]] stood at $16.63 billion and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP per capita]] was $1,000.&lt;ref name=CIA-GDP-PPP&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2004.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af |title=GDP - per capita (PPP): $1,000 (2010 est.)|work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|accessdate=2010-10-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; Its unemployment rate is 35%&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2129.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af |title=35% (2008 est.)|work=The World Factbook|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|accessdate=2010-10-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; and roughly 36% of its citizens live below the poverty line.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2046.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af |title=36% (FY08/09) |work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|accessdate=2010-10-20}}&lt;/ref&gt; About 42 percent of the population live on less than $1 a day, according to USAID.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=83417|title=Afghanistan: Food still unaffordable for millions|work=|publisher=[[IRIN]]|date=March 12, 2009|accessdate=2010-10-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, due to the infusion of multi-billion dollars in international assistance and investments, as well as remittances from expats, the economy has steadily improved, growing at approximately 12 percent per year during the past six years.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov//en/Page.CountryOverview.aspx |title=USAID/Afghanistan Strategy |work=|publisher=USAID|accessdate=2010-10-20}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is also due to improvements in [[Ministry of Agriculture, Irrigation &amp; Livestock (Afghanistan)|agricultural production]], which is the backbone of the nation's economy since over 75% of its citizens are involved in this field.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Program.19c.aspx |title=Objective: Accelerating market-led growth in agriculture|work=|publisher=USAID|accessdate=2010-10-20}}{{dead link|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Program.19c.aspx|date=May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:Afghan pomegranate processing.jpg|thumb|Workers processing [[pomegranate production in Afghanistan|pomegranate]]s (''anaar''), which Afghanistan is famous for in Asia.]]

One of the main drivers for the current economic recovery is the return of over 5 million [[Afghan diaspora|Afghan expatriates]], who brought with them fresh energy, entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses. The [[Afghan rug]]s have become a popular product again and this gives the large number of rug weavers in the country a chance to earn more income. While the country's current account deficit is largely financed with the donor money, only a small portion is provided directly to the government budget. The rest is provided to non-budgetary expenditure and donor-designated projects through the United Nations system and [[non-governmental organization]]s.

The [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Finance]] is focusing on improved revenue collection and public sector expenditure discipline. Since 2003, over 16 new banks have opened in the country, including [[Afghanistan International Bank]], [[Kabul Bank]], [[Azizi Bank]], [[Pashtany Bank]], [[Standard Chartered Bank]], [[First Micro Finance Bank]], and others. [[Da Afghanistan Bank]] serves as the [[central bank]] of the nation and the [[Afghan afghani|&quot;Afghani&quot;]] (AFN) is the [[national currency]], with an exchange rate of 50 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.

Afghanistan is a member of the [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation|SAARC]], [[Economic Cooperation Organization|ECO]] and the [[Economy of the OIC|OIC]]. It is known for producing some of the finest [[pomegranate]]s, [[grapes]], [[apricot]]s, [[melon]]s, and several other fresh and [[Dried fruit|dry fruits]], including [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=49291 Exporting Afghanistan], by P.J. Tobia. Nov 17, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; According to the [[World Bank]], &quot;economic growth has been strong and has generated better livelihoods&quot; since late 2001.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPPOVRED/0,,contentMDK:20574056~menuPK:493447~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:493441,00.html |title=Poverty Reduction – Poverty in Afghanistan |publisher=Web.worldbank.org |date= |accessdate=2009-12-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Opium production in Afghanistan]] has soared to a record in 2007 with about 3 million Afghans reported to be involved in the business&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.guardian.co.uk/afghanistan/story/0,,2157313,00.html UN horrified by surge in opium trade in Helmand].&lt;/ref&gt; but then declined significantly in the years following.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/frontpage/2009/September/afghan-opium-production-in-significant--decline.html Afghan opium production in significant decline], [[UNDOC]]&lt;/ref&gt; The government started programs to help reduce cultivation of poppy, and by 2010 it was reported that 24 out of the 34 provinces were free from poppy grow.

===Energy and mining===
{{Main|Mining in Afghanistan}}
According to recent U.S. Geological surveys that were funded by the [[Council of Ministers (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Mines and Industry]], Afghanistan may be possessing up to {{convert|36|Tcuft|km3}} of [[natural gas]], {{convert|3.6|Goilbbl|m3}} of [[petroleum]] and up to {{convert|1325|Moilbbl|m3}} of [[natural gas liquids]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Eurasianet&quot;&gt;[http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/eav090306.shtml ''Afghanistan’s Energy Future and its Potential Implications''], Eurasianet.org.&lt;/ref&gt; Other recent reports show that the country has huge amounts of gold, copper, coal, [[iron ore]] and other [[minerals]].&lt;ref name=&quot;CIA-natural-resources&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2111.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af |title=Natural resources: Afghanistan |work=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA |accessdate=2010-12-04}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;mom&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mom.gov.af/uploads/files/English/USGS%20Report/8.0-chemical-sedimentry-FINAL.pdf |title=8.0 Chemical-sedimentary deposits |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-11-14}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;bgs&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/AfghanMinerals/docs/Gold_A4.pdf#search='gold%20and%20copper%20discovered%20in%20afghanistan' |title=Minerals in Afghanistan |publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] |accessdate=2010-12-04}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;uranium&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.wise-uranium.org/uissr05.html#OPER |title=Uranium Mining Issues: 2005 Review |publisher=Wise Uranium Project |accessdate=2010-12-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2010, [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] officials along with geologists from the United States announced the discovery of $1–3 trillion worth untapped mineral deposits in Afghanistan.&lt;ref name=&quot;NYT&quot; /&gt; Afghan officials assert that &quot;this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy&quot; and a memo from the Pentagon stated that Afghanistan could become the &quot;Saudi Arabia of [[lithium]]&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://news.discovery.com/earth/afghanistan-minerals-lithium.html |title=Afghanistan: The Saudi Arabia of Lithium? |publisher=News.discovery.com |date=2010-06-14 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=204154 |title=Afghanistan is suddenly wealthy: US finds $1 trillion in mineral deposits |publisher=Ksdk.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/afghanistans-resources-could-make-it-the-richest-mining-region-on-earth-2000507.html |title=Afghanistan's resources could make it the richest mining region on earth |publisher=Independent.co.uk |date= 2010-06-15|accessdate=2010-11-14 |location=London |first=Kim |last=Sengupta}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/natural_resources/article7149696.ece|location=London|work=The Times|title=Taleban zones mineral riches may rival Saudi Arabia says Pentagon|first1=Jeremy|last1=Page|first2=Michael|last2=Evans|date=2010-06-15}}&lt;/ref&gt; The government is preparing deals to extract its copper and iron reserves, which could earn billions of dollars in [[royalties]] and taxes every year for the next 100 years. Analysts believe that if the Afghan state was to generate even $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its [[gross national product]] would double and provide long-term funding for Afghan security forces and other critical needs.&lt;ref&gt;O'Hanlon, Michael E. [http://www.brookings.edu/opinions/2010/0616_afghanistan_minerals_ohanlon.aspx &quot;Deposits Could Aid Ailing Afghanistan&quot;], [http://www.brookings.edu/ The Brookings Institution], 16 June 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Transport and communications===
{{Main|Transport in Afghanistan|Communications in Afghanistan}}
[[File:Ariana Afghan A310-300 F-GEMO.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ariana Afghan Airlines]]]]
[[Ariana Afghan Airlines]] is the national carrier, with domestic flights between Kabul, Kandahar, Herat and Mazar-i-Sharif. International flights include to [[Dubai]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Istanbul]] and a number of other Asian destinations.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://flyariana.com/schedules.php# |title=Ariana |publisher=Flyariana.com |date= |accessdate=2009-12-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; There are also limited domestic and international flight services available from the locally owned [[Kam Air]], [[Pamir Airways]] and [[Safi Airways]].

The country has limited [[Rail transport in Afghanistan|rail service]] with Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan in the north. There are two other railway projects currently in progress with neighboring nations, one is between Herat and Iran while another is to connect with [[Pakistan Railways]]. Citizens who travel far distances use bus services. Newer automobiles have recently become more widely available after the rebuilding of roads and highways. Vehicles are imported from the [[United Arab Emirates]] through Pakistan and Iran. [[Postage stamps and postal history of Afghanistan|Postal]] and package delivery services such as [[FedEx]], [[DHL]] and others are found in major cities and towns.

Telecommunication services in the country are provided by [[Afghan Wireless]], [[Etisalat]], [[Roshan (telco)|Roshan]], [[MTN Group]] and [[Afghan Telecom]]. In 2006, the [[Ministry of Communications (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Communications]] signed a $64.5 million agreement with [[ZTE]] for the establishment of a countrywide [[optical fiber cable]] network. As of 2009, the country has 129,300 [[landline|fixed telephone lines]],&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2150.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA.gov]&lt;/ref&gt; about 12 million [[mobile phone]] subscribers&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2151.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA.Gov]&lt;/ref&gt; and 1 million [[internet]] users.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2153.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA.gov]&lt;/ref&gt;

===Media===
{{Main|Media of Afghanistan}}
The [[Media of Afghanistan|Afghan media]] began in the early 20th century, with the first newspaper being published in 1906. By the 1920s, [[Radio Kabul]] was broadcasting local radio services. [[Afghanistan National Television]] was launched in 1974 but was closed in 1996 when the media was tightly controlled by the Taliban.&lt;ref name=dart&gt;Dartnell, M. Y. ''Insurgency Online: Web Activism and Global Conflict.'' University of Toronto Press, 2006. ISBN 978-0-8020-8553-5.&lt;/ref&gt; Since 2002, press restrictions were gradually relaxed and private media diversified. [[Freedom of expression]] and the press is promoted in the 2004 constitution and [[censorship]] is banned, though [[defamation|defaming]] individuals or producing material contrary to the principles of Islam is prohibited. In 2008, [[Reporters Without Borders]] listed the media environment as 156 out of 173, with 1st being most free. 400 publications are now registered, at least 15 local [[List of television channels in Afghanistan|Afghan television channels]] and 60 radio stations.&lt;ref name=fh&gt;[http://www.freedomhouse.org/template.cfm?page=251&amp;year=2008 Afghanistan Press Report 2008], ''Freedom House''.&lt;/ref&gt; Foreign radio stations, such as [[Voice of America]] and [[BBC World Service]], also broadcast into the country.

==Demographics==
{{Main|Demography of Afghanistan|Afghan refugees}}
As of July 2010, the population of Afghanistan is around 28,395,716,&lt;ref name=&quot;CIA-pop&quot;&gt;{{cite web| url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2119.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af|title=Population of Afghanistan |work=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA |year=2010|accessdate=2010-10-12}}&lt;/ref&gt; but it is unknown if the 3 million [[Afghan refugees]] living in [[Afghans in Pakistan|Pakistan]] and [[Afghans in Iran|Iran]] are included or not. A 2009 UN estimate shows that the Afghan population was 28,150,000&lt;ref name=unpop&gt;{{Cite journal| url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/wpp2008/wpp2008_text_tables.pdf | title=World Population Prospects, Table A.1 |version=2008 revision|format=PDF|publisher=United Nations |work=Department of Economic and Social Affairs Population Division |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-03-12}}&lt;/ref&gt; and a 2009–2010 nationwide [[statistical survey]] conducted by the [[Central Statistics Office (Afghanistan)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) of Afghanistan has put it at 26 million but not counting some parts of the country due to insecurity.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.pajhwok.com/viewstory.asp?lng=eng&amp;id=99681 |title=CSO census puts population at 26 million |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |work=Rahmatullah Afghan |publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News |date=August 4, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;

A partial [[census]] conducted in 1979 showed roughly 15.5 million people living in the country.&lt;ref name=&quot;IIOT&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.gl.iit.edu/govdocs/afghanistan/Afghanistan-Chapter2.pdf |title=Chapter 2. The Society and Its Environment |format=PDF |work=Afghanistan Country Study |publisher=[[Illinois Institute of Technology]]|pages=105–06 |accessdate=2010-10-12}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Statistical Yearbook published in 1983 by the [[Babrak Karmal]] government claimed a total population of 15.96 million for 1981-82.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/afghanistan/36.htm |title=Population |publisher=U.S. Library of Congress |year=2008 |accessdate=2010-10-12}}&lt;/ref&gt; Between 600,000 to 2 million Afghans were killed during the various 1979-2001 wars, majority of them during the Soviet war in the 1980s.&lt;ref name=&quot;erols1979&quot;/&gt; At least 5 million more fled the country to neighboring Pakistan and Iran. According to the [[Population Reference Bureau]], the Afghan population is estimated to increase to 82 million by 2050.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.prb.org/Countries/Afghanistan.aspx |title=Afghanistan – Population Reference Bureau |publisher=[[Population Reference Bureau]] |date= |accessdate=2009-12-29}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The only city in Afghanistan with over two million residents is its capital, Kabul. The other major cities in the country are, in order of population size, [[Kandahar]], [[Herat]], [[Mazar-e Sharif]], [[Jalalabad]], [[Ghazni]], [[Kunduz]], [[Farah, Afghanistan|Farah]]. Urban areas are experiencing rapid population growth following the return of over 5 million Afghan expats from Pakistan and Iran.

===Ethnic groups===
{{Main|Ethnic groups in Afghanistan}}
[[File:US Army ethnolinguistic map of Afghanistan -- circa 2001-09.jpg|thumb|[[Ethnolinguistics|Ethnolinguistic]] groups of Afghanistan]]
Afghanistan is a [[multiethnic society]]. The population of the country is divided into a wide variety of [[ethnolinguistics|ethnolinguistic]] groups. Because a systematic census has not been held in the nation in decades, exact figures about the size and composition of the various [[ethnic group]]s are unvailable.&lt;ref&gt;[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3717092.stm Afghan poll's ethnic battleground]  2004-10-06. BBC&lt;/ref&gt; In this regard, the [[Encyclopædia Britannica]] states:{{quote|''No national census has been conducted in Afghanistan since a partial count in 1979, and years of war and population dislocation have made an accurate ethnic count impossible. Current population estimates are therefore rough approximations, which show that Pashtuns comprise somewhat less than two-fifths of the population. The two largest Pashtun tribal groups are the Durrani and Ghilzay. Tajiks are likely to account for some one-fourth of Afghans and Hazara nearly one-fifth. Uzbeks and Chahar Aimaks each account for slightly more than 5 percent of the population and Turkmen an even smaller portion.''&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/7798/Afghanistan |title=(Ethnic groups) |publisher=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;}}
An approximate distribution of the nation's total ethnic groups is shown in the line chart below:
